<kml xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/kml/2.2">
<Document>
<name>Iceland Ring Road — South</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Iceland Ring Road — South</h2><p><i>Iceland · Route 1, Reykjavík to Höfn</i></p><p><b>460 km of waterfalls, black-sand beaches, glacier tongues, and an iceberg lagoon.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>385 km (239 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>2–3 days minimum</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>Mid-June–early September for full daylight and open routes; September for northern lights with mild conditions</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Sudden weather (snow possible any month); single-lane bridges; rivers fording on side roads (not main route); sheep; geothermal soft ground</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>471</td></tr></table><hr><p>Route 1 (Hringvegur) circles all of Iceland — 1,332 km in total. The southern stretch from Reykjavík to Höfn covers the country's geological greatest hits: the volcanic system that erupted in 2010 (Eyjafjallajökull) and 2021–24 (Reykjanes); the waterfalls Seljalandsfoss (you walk behind it) and Skógafoss; the black-sand beach at Reynisfjara with its prismatic basalt columns; the lava field laid down in the 1783 Laki eruption (which killed a quarter of Iceland's population through famine); Skaftafell and the southeast glaciers; and Jökulsárlón, where icebergs calved from Vatnajökull drift through a lagoon and out to sea, washing back ashore at Diamond Beach.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Seljalandsfoss</b> — 60 m waterfall you can walk all the way around — there's a path behind the curtain of water. Get wet. Bring a waterproof for the camera.</li><li><b>Skógafoss</b> — 60 m, 25 m wide. A staircase climbs the east side to a top viewing platform; the Fimmvörðuháls trail up to the volcano starts here.</li><li><b>Reynisfjara</b> — Black-sand beach with hexagonal basalt columns and the Reynisdrangar sea-stacks offshore (legendary trolls turned to stone by the dawn). DANGEROUS sneaker waves; stay well back from the water.</li><li><b>Eldhraun lava field</b> — Velvet-green moss carpets the lava from the 1783–84 Laki eruption, the largest known basalt flow in human history. Stay on marked paths — the moss is fragile and slow-growing.</li><li><b>Skaftafell / Svínafellsjökull</b> — Glacier tongue you can walk to the foot of (with a guide for ice walks). The peak Hvannadalshnúkur (2,110 m) is Iceland's highest. Used as filming location in Interstellar.</li><li><b>Jökulsárlón</b> — Iceberg-filled lagoon where the Breiðamerkurjökull glacier calves into the sea. Ice has darkened over 1,000 years of compression; the blue color is from light absorption. Boat tours weave through the bergs.</li><li><b>Diamond Beach</b> — Across the road from Jökulsárlón. Icebergs that have drifted out of the lagoon wash up on black sand — translucent ice on jet sand looks like jewelry on velvet.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
